<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
  <div class="mt-4 px-4 py-4" style="background-color: white; max-width: 900px; text-align: center; border-radius: 10px;">
    <h3 class="text-success mb-3">Problematic and Solution</h3>
    <p class="fw-medium">
      We conducted these interviews to better understand the current reality faced by cyclists in our community. Through their voices, we were able to identify not only the positive aspects of cycling—such as physical health, mental well-being, and environmental benefits—but also the challenges they experience on a daily basis, particularly regarding safety and road coexistence.
      <br/><br/>
      Many of the participants shared responsible habits, such as using helmets, lights, and following traffic regulations. However, we also observed that not all cyclists maintain consistent safety practices. Some neglect basic precautions, whether due to lack of education, confidence, or simply habit. These testimonies confirm that insecurity on the road is a recurring concern, and not all users are fully prepared or protected.
      <br/><br/>
      We recognize that achieving a complete and effective solution is complex. Changing behavior and increasing awareness are long-term challenges that go hand in hand with education, culture, and urban policy. It is unrealistic to think that safety can be guaranteed 100%, especially when individual responsibility, government support, and infrastructure must all work together. However, this complexity does not stop us from acting.
      <br/><br/>
      Our main goal is to promote the health and safety of cyclists. We believe that even small changes can have a meaningful impact. Raising awareness, providing access to protective gear, and encouraging a culture of mutual respect on the road are essential steps. Promoting these values is our way of contributing to a safer, healthier, and more conscious cycling community.
      <br/><br/>
      As a possible approach, we suggest a realistic and scalable educational campaign focused on everyday practices, supported by workshops, informative materials, and community engagement. Rather than offering a perfect solution, we aim to start a movement that gradually improves conditions and strengthens a sense of care and responsibility among all road users.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
